re done.{&1310}\par That particular dream always left me rubbing just beneath my shoulder for a few days afterwards. Where the thing had stabbed me right through. Or Brennan, I mean. I kept expecting to find a bleeding hole there like he had.{&1310}\par "So what were you doing just before it happened this time?"{&1310}\par The episode, she meant. They didn't happen so frequently that anyone could ever give a good explanation, though Elle tried. My last one had been months ago.{&1310}\par I shrugged my shoulders. I could never really remember afterwards.{&1310}\par "Was Dr. Holloway talking?"{&1310}\par "I guess so."{&1310}\par "About what?"{&1310}\par Again, I shrugged. I'd heard most of it all before over the course of seven semesters. He only spiced a few details up in his lectures, so I mostly spaced out a lot of the time. Sometimes I imagined levitating one of those practice balls and tossing it right at his balding head.{&1310}\par "I don't know. Maybe something about ... subspace particles? I think?"{&1310}\par "Subspace ... \i particles\i0  ..."{&1310}\par She looked at me, hard. {&1310}\par "That's the best you could come up with? Really?"{&1310}\par And sighed, looking down at her pad.{&1310}\par "I'm beginning to see why Dr. Holloway gets so frustrated with you."{&1310}\par "He hates me because I can't do anything," I tossed back.{&1310}\par "Maybe you're not trying hard enough."{&1310}\par "I am. I've tried everything he's told me to do. I've taken the course seven times. Seven times! Nothing works."{&1310}\par She opened her mouth, but I shut her down quickly.{&1310}\par "Dad just keeps making me go because he wants me to prove I can actually do something. Anything." {&1310}\par "Because the alternative would be ...?" she offered.{&1310}\par "That I'm just mundane. Like everyone thinks."{&1310}\par "And you think he's afraid of that being true?"{&1310}\par And there it was.{&1310}\par "Yes."{&1310}\par "Hm."{&1310}\par Elle sat there for a while with her fists balled under her chin and a thoughtful look on her face. I had opened my eyes again, giving her a tired, irritated stare. It was obvious to me - the whole thing, that is. Maybe dad didn't even realize it. He certainly never would have admitted it to me, that's for sure.{&1310}\par Eventually, Elle came out of that introspection and gently dipped her clasped fingers in my direction.{&1310}\par "Maybe he has a different reason for putting you through all that," she ventured, drawing the words out slowly and with some weight. I just shook my head.{&1310}\par My watch beeped.{&1310}\par "Time's up," I sighed wearily at that. "Anything else?"{&1310}\par "Do you have anything else for \i me\i0 , Evelyn," she countered with a genuine smile.{&1310}\par "No. I don't think so."{&1310}\par "What about things with ..." she trailed, hinting.{&1310}\par My face flushed hard before she could even finish the sentence. And I stomped all over it before she could even think to.{&1310}\par "Nope. Nothing new."{&1310}\par "Hmm," she mused, smiling way too much at me. She was an old woman - old, like most of the brainiacs wandering around with pet projects and algorithms and fantasies about theoretical breakthroughs in their heads around there. And sometimes I wondered if I was the most interesting thing she could poke and prod intangible fingers at all day. Unlike a lot of the other doctorates around Riftwatch, she specialized in psychology. I didn't think it was too hard to believe she got her kicks out of playing mind games with people.{&1310}\par "Well, alright then. You are - free to go," she joked at my expense with a generous bob of her head.{&1310}\par I rolled my eyes back at her, still flush. Then I got up with a heavy sigh, said my thank you's and goodbyes, and left.\cf2\f2 {&1310}\par }{&1310}
